  "prompt": "What is it like to be an Indian student and get your US Visa rejected?",
  "response": "Getting a US visa rejected can be a deeply emotional and challenging experience for an Indian student. Here's a typical perspective:\n\nEmotional Impact:\n- Feelings of disappointment and frustration\n- Sense of personal failure\n- Anxiety about future academic and career plans\n- Potential embarrassment within family and social circles\n\nCommon Reasons for Rejection:\n- Insufficient financial documentation\n- Doubts about intent to return to India\n- Incomplete or incorrect application\n- Limited proof of strong ties to home country\n- Perceived risk of staying in the US permanently\n\nPractical Consequences:\n- Delayed academic/career goals\n- Additional visa application costs\n- Need to reapply with stronger documentation\n- Potential loss of university admission or scholarship\n- Emotional stress and uncertainty\n\nTypical Psychological Response:\n- Initial shock and disbelief\n- Self-doubt and questioning personal capabilities\n- Stress about explaining rejection to family\n- Motivation to understand rejection reasons\n- Determination to improve application next time\n\nTypical Next Steps:\n- Carefully review rejection reasons\n- Consult immigration experts\n- Strengthen financial and documentation evidence\n- Prepare more comprehensive application\n- Consider alternative study destinations\n\nThe experience is often a mix of disappointment, learning, and resilience for most Indian students.",
